The following regulated RMP-regulated substances are maintained onsite: ammonia, chlorine, and hydrogen chloride.  These chemicals are stored in cylinders of varying sizes.  The cylinders are delivered to the facility on pallets either by an outside vendor or intercompany trucks. They are stored on or near the dock and remain onsite until purchased by a customer, at which point the intercompany truck picks up the cylinders for delivery to the customer. 



The maximum intended inventory for each of the chemicals is listed as follows:

Ammonia: 22,500 pounds

Chlorine: 6,720 pounds

Hydrogen Chloride: 6,835 pounds



Accidental Release Prevention Program



Matheson Tri-Gas has developed a Process Safety Management and Risk Management Program to manage the handling of the regulated substances. The program includes but is not limited to the following elements:



1) Safety information that describes the chemical hazards and technical specifications for the process equipment;

2) Written procedures for handling and inspecting the cylinders;

3) Training for employees involved with cylinder handling and inspection;

4) Written procedures for safely introducing modifications to the covered processes;

5) Investigating releases and near misses and implementing measures to prevent recurrence;

6) Written procedures for conducting hot work on or near the covered processes;

7) Contractor management policies to ensure contract employee safety while on facility premises; and

8) Employee involvement in program development and implementation.



In addition, engineering and administrative controls are implemented to reduce the chance of an accidental release to the environment.  Most cylinders are equipped with a fusible relief plug which protects the equipment from overpressurization and rupture.  Detectors are installed in the dock area where the cylinders are stored to warn personnel of a leak.  The cylinders are inspected upon delivery, and any
